**Key finding:** The corpus's chapter 1 is the Preface (political exhortation only); the formal inalienability argument is in corpus chapter 2 (the "Speech"). Fichte gives three interlocking reasons why thought-freedom cannot be alienated: (1) freedom and personality are preconditions of any moral law at all, making them inalienable by definition; (2) free thought is constitutive of rational personhood — any contract to surrender it is a self-contradictory promise to become an animal; (3) reason by its nature strives toward the infinite and cannot recognize an absolute boundary — limiting inquiry would require reason to become irrational at the limit, which is incoherent.
